This is about systemd vs kernel (bios) interface naming ...

centaurisoho can handle both name shemes including explicit interface naming
via link files. These things and why the default is to use kernel names  are
discussed in detail in the documentation.

The NamePolicy can be set by kernel command line or by systemd config. The
most reliable way to turn systemd interface names off is the kernel boot
parameter 'net.ifnames=0'.

When creating 'ln -s /dev/null /etc/systemd/network/99-default.link' you must
also run run 'update-initramfs -u' and reboot to switch to kernel naming! 
Wheras the kernel boot parameter becomes effective at the next boot without
touching the initrd.

This is why centaurisoho uses the kernel boot parameter. The boot commands are
autogenerated by either centauriraspi, centauriefilinux or the grub.cfg file.
By default all of them add 'net.ifnames=0' if '99-default.link' is '/dev/null'
The tools centauriraspi and centauriefilinux can override this by option

    --ifnames=0            use kernel naming
    --ifnames=1            use systemd naming
    --ifnames=2 (default)  first check '99-default-link' or 'option sysdnames'
                           otherwise.  See centaurinetcfg 'option sysdnames'.

Unfortunately managing the boot configuration and initrd is a non-trival task.
The tool 'centaurinetgen naming' should be used the show the current state or
to change the settings:

    centaurinetgen naming               show current setting
    centaurinetgen naming kernel        set kernel (bios) naming
    centaurinetgen naming systemd       set systemd naming
    centaurinetgen naming default       same logic as --ifnames=2

Centaurinetgen can update boot parameters and initrd.

At reboot time the service 'centaurisysinit' gets started and updates managed
files in '/etc/network' to the selected naming mode. It uses the current
system name policy, so the interface configuration will be modified if needed
to let the system have network connectivity ...
                    
    kernel net.ifnames=0            no  yes no  yes no  yes no  yes
    initrd with 99-default.link     no  no  yes yes no  no  yes yes
    99-default.link                 no  no  no  no  yes yes yes yes
    ---------------------------------------------------------------
    use kernel names at boot        no  yes yes yes no  yes yes yes


Cloning/renanming with name policy change
=========================================

The network configuration in /etc/default/centarinetcfg determins the naming
policy of hosts via 'option sysdnames <host>'. So when cloning/renaming a
host the naming policy may change.

The following tools can be used to clone or rename a system image:

    centauridisk            (updates grub.cfg)
    centaurirestore         (updates grub.cfg) 
    centaurisoho clone      (updates grub.cfg and systemd-boot)
    centaurisoho restore    (updates grub.cfg)

These tools always fix grub settings but only centaurisoho also updates systemd-boot.
So after the first boot of a cloned/renamed system it might be neccessary to run
'centaurinetgen naming' to update boot systemd-boot parameters and the initde.

***

